[
    {
        "index": 1,
        "start_time": 10947,
        "end_time": 18489,
        "text": "One, two, three, four, five, six,\nseven, eight, nine, and zero."
    },
    {
        "index": 2,
        "start_time": 18489,
        "end_time": 24188,
        "text": "With just these ten symbols, we can\nwrite any rational number imaginable."
    },
    {
        "index": 3,
        "start_time": 24188,
        "end_time": 26691,
        "text": "But why these particular symbols?"
    },
    {
        "index": 4,
        "start_time": 26691,
        "end_time": 28352,
        "text": "Why ten of them?"
    },
    {
        "index": 5,
        "start_time": 28352,
        "end_time": 31599,
        "text": "And why do we arrange them the way we do?"
    },
    {
        "index": 6,
        "start_time": 31599,
        "end_time": 35419,
        "text": "Numbers have been a fact of life\nthroughout recorded history."
    },
    {
        "index": 7,
        "start_time": 35419,
        "end_time": 39849,
        "text": "Early humans likely counted animals\nin a flock or members in a tribe"
    },
    {
        "index": 8,
        "start_time": 39849,
        "end_time": 42989,
        "text": "using body parts or tally marks."
    },
    {
        "index": 9,
        "start_time": 42989,
        "end_time": 47480,
        "text": "But as the complexity of life increased,\nalong with the number of things to count,"
    },
    {
        "index": 10,
        "start_time": 47480,
        "end_time": 50550,
        "text": "these methods were no longer sufficient."
    },
    {
        "index": 11,
        "start_time": 50550,
        "end_time": 52049,
        "text": "So as they developed,"
    },
    {
        "index": 12,
        "start_time": 52049,
        "end_time": 56808,
        "text": "different civilizations came up \nwith ways of recording higher numbers."
    },
    {
        "index": 13,
        "start_time": 56808,
        "end_time": 58059,
        "text": "Many of these systems,"
    },
    {
        "index": 14,
        "start_time": 58059,
        "end_time": 58819,
        "text": "like Greek,"
    },
    {
        "index": 15,
        "start_time": 58819,
        "end_time": 59539,
        "text": "Hebrew,"
    },
    {
        "index": 16,
        "start_time": 59539,
        "end_time": 60770,
        "text": "and Egyptian numerals,"
    },
    {
        "index": 17,
        "start_time": 60770,
        "end_time": 63300,
        "text": "were just extensions of tally marks"
    },
    {
        "index": 18,
        "start_time": 63300,
        "end_time": 67350,
        "text": "with new symbols added to represent\nlarger magnitudes of value."
    },
    {
        "index": 19,
        "start_time": 67350,
        "end_time": 73150,
        "text": "Each symbol was repeated as many times\nas necessary and all were added together."
    },
    {
        "index": 20,
        "start_time": 73150,
        "end_time": 75990,
        "text": "Roman numerals added another twist."
    },
    {
        "index": 21,
        "start_time": 75990,
        "end_time": 78490,
        "text": "If a numeral appeared before one\nwith a higher value,"
    },
    {
        "index": 22,
        "start_time": 78490,
        "end_time": 81950,
        "text": "it would be subtracted rather than added."
    },
    {
        "index": 23,
        "start_time": 81950,
        "end_time": 83450,
        "text": "But even with this innovation,"
    },
    {
        "index": 24,
        "start_time": 83450,
        "end_time": 88501,
        "text": "it was still a cumbersome method\nfor writing large numbers."
    },
    {
        "index": 25,
        "start_time": 88501,
        "end_time": 90861,
        "text": "The way to a more useful \nand elegant system"
    },
    {
        "index": 26,
        "start_time": 90861,
        "end_time": 95041,
        "text": "lay in something called \npositional notation."
    },
    {
        "index": 27,
        "start_time": 95041,
        "end_time": 98430,
        "text": "Previous number systems needed to draw\nmany symbols repeatedly"
    },
    {
        "index": 28,
        "start_time": 98430,
        "end_time": 102610,
        "text": "and invent a new symbol \nfor each larger magnitude."
    },
    {
        "index": 29,
        "start_time": 102610,
        "end_time": 105971,
        "text": "But a positional system could reuse\nthe same symbols,"
    },
    {
        "index": 30,
        "start_time": 105971,
        "end_time": 110962,
        "text": "assigning them different values\nbased on their position in the sequence."
    },
    {
        "index": 31,
        "start_time": 110962,
        "end_time": 114911,
        "text": "Several civilizations developed positional\nnotation independently,"
    },
    {
        "index": 32,
        "start_time": 114911,
        "end_time": 116822,
        "text": "including the Babylonians,"
    },
    {
        "index": 33,
        "start_time": 116822,
        "end_time": 118032,
        "text": "the Ancient Chinese,"
    },
    {
        "index": 34,
        "start_time": 118032,
        "end_time": 119982,
        "text": "and the Aztecs."
    },
    {
        "index": 35,
        "start_time": 119982,
        "end_time": 124562,
        "text": "By the 8th century, Indian mathematicians\nhad perfected such a system"
    },
    {
        "index": 36,
        "start_time": 124562,
        "end_time": 126552,
        "text": "and over the next several centuries,"
    },
    {
        "index": 37,
        "start_time": 126552,
        "end_time": 132343,
        "text": "Arab merchants, scholars, and conquerors\nbegan to spread it into Europe."
    },
    {
        "index": 38,
        "start_time": 132343,
        "end_time": 136043,
        "text": "This was a decimal, or base ten, system,"
    },
    {
        "index": 39,
        "start_time": 136043,
        "end_time": 140514,
        "text": "which could represent any number\nusing only ten unique glyphs."
    },
    {
        "index": 40,
        "start_time": 140514,
        "end_time": 143943,
        "text": "The positions of these symbols\nindicate different powers of ten,"
    },
    {
        "index": 41,
        "start_time": 143943,
        "end_time": 147483,
        "text": "starting on the right \nand increasing as we move left."
    },
    {
        "index": 42,
        "start_time": 147483,
        "end_time": 150203,
        "text": "For example, the number 316"
    },
    {
        "index": 43,
        "start_time": 150203,
        "end_time": 153693,
        "text": "reads as 6x10^0"
    },
    {
        "index": 44,
        "start_time": 153693,
        "end_time": 156292,
        "text": "plus 1x10^1"
    },
    {
        "index": 45,
        "start_time": 156292,
        "end_time": 159943,
        "text": "plus 3x10^2."
    },
    {
        "index": 46,
        "start_time": 159943,
        "end_time": 161833,
        "text": "A key breakthrough of this system,"
    },
    {
        "index": 47,
        "start_time": 161833,
        "end_time": 164734,
        "text": "which was also independently \ndeveloped by the Mayans,"
    },
    {
        "index": 48,
        "start_time": 164734,
        "end_time": 167483,
        "text": "was the number zero."
    },
    {
        "index": 49,
        "start_time": 167483,
        "end_time": 170573,
        "text": "Older positional notation systems \nthat lacked this symbol"
    },
    {
        "index": 50,
        "start_time": 170573,
        "end_time": 172394,
        "text": "would leave a blank in its place,"
    },
    {
        "index": 51,
        "start_time": 172394,
        "end_time": 176935,
        "text": "making it hard to distinguish \nbetween 63 and 603,"
    },
    {
        "index": 52,
        "start_time": 176935,
        "end_time": 180003,
        "text": "or 12 and 120."
    },
    {
        "index": 53,
        "start_time": 180003,
        "end_time": 184054,
        "text": "The understanding of zero as both\na value and a placeholder"
    },
    {
        "index": 54,
        "start_time": 184054,
        "end_time": 188024,
        "text": "made for reliable and consistent notation."
    },
    {
        "index": 55,
        "start_time": 188024,
        "end_time": 190393,
        "text": "Of course, it&#39;s possible \nto use any ten symbols"
    },
    {
        "index": 56,
        "start_time": 190393,
        "end_time": 193743,
        "text": "to represent the numerals \nzero through nine."
    },
    {
        "index": 57,
        "start_time": 193743,
        "end_time": 197038,
        "text": "For a long time, \nthe glyphs varied regionally."
    },
    {
        "index": 58,
        "start_time": 197038,
        "end_time": 199202,
        "text": "Most scholars agree \nthat our current digits"
    },
    {
        "index": 59,
        "start_time": 199202,
        "end_time": 202726,
        "text": "evolved from those used in the\nNorth African Maghreb region"
    },
    {
        "index": 60,
        "start_time": 202726,
        "end_time": 204884,
        "text": "of the Arab Empire."
    },
    {
        "index": 61,
        "start_time": 204884,
        "end_time": 209905,
        "text": "And by the 15th century, what we now know\nas the Hindu-Arabic numeral system"
    },
    {
        "index": 62,
        "start_time": 209905,
        "end_time": 212789,
        "text": "had replaced Roman numerals\nin everyday life"
    },
    {
        "index": 63,
        "start_time": 212789,
        "end_time": 217275,
        "text": "to become the most commonly \nused number system in the world."
    },
    {
        "index": 64,
        "start_time": 217275,
        "end_time": 220726,
        "text": "So why did the Hindu-Arabic system,\nalong with so many others,"
    },
    {
        "index": 65,
        "start_time": 220726,
        "end_time": 222859,
        "text": "use base ten?"
    },
    {
        "index": 66,
        "start_time": 222859,
        "end_time": 226784,
        "text": "The most likely answer is the simplest."
    },
    {
        "index": 67,
        "start_time": 226784,
        "end_time": 232355,
        "text": "That also explains why the Aztecs used\na base 20, or vigesimal system."
    },
    {
        "index": 68,
        "start_time": 232355,
        "end_time": 234975,
        "text": "But other bases are possible, too."
    },
    {
        "index": 69,
        "start_time": 234975,
        "end_time": 238965,
        "text": "Babylonian numerals were sexigesimal,\nor base 60."
    },
    {
        "index": 70,
        "start_time": 238965,
        "end_time": 242236,
        "text": "Any many people think that a base 12,\nor duodecimal system,"
    },
    {
        "index": 71,
        "start_time": 242236,
        "end_time": 244345,
        "text": "would be a good idea."
    },
    {
        "index": 72,
        "start_time": 244345,
        "end_time": 248265,
        "text": "Like 60, 12 is a highly composite number\nthat can be divided by two,"
    },
    {
        "index": 73,
        "start_time": 248265,
        "end_time": 249035,
        "text": "three,"
    },
    {
        "index": 74,
        "start_time": 249035,
        "end_time": 249747,
        "text": "four,"
    },
    {
        "index": 75,
        "start_time": 249747,
        "end_time": 250926,
        "text": "and six,"
    },
    {
        "index": 76,
        "start_time": 250926,
        "end_time": 254705,
        "text": "making it much better for representing\ncommon fractions."
    },
    {
        "index": 77,
        "start_time": 254705,
        "end_time": 257755,
        "text": "In fact, both systems appear\nin our everyday lives,"
    },
    {
        "index": 78,
        "start_time": 257755,
        "end_time": 259871,
        "text": "from how we measure degrees and time,"
    },
    {
        "index": 79,
        "start_time": 259871,
        "end_time": 263416,
        "text": "to common measurements,\nlike a dozen or a gross."
    },
    {
        "index": 80,
        "start_time": 263416,
        "end_time": 267166,
        "text": "And, of course, the base two, \nor binary system,"
    },
    {
        "index": 81,
        "start_time": 267166,
        "end_time": 270048,
        "text": "is used in all of our digital devices,"
    },
    {
        "index": 82,
        "start_time": 270048,
        "end_time": 275966,
        "text": "though programmers also use base eight\nand base 16 for more compact notation."
    },
    {
        "index": 83,
        "start_time": 275966,
        "end_time": 277990,
        "text": "So the next time you use a large number,"
    },
    {
        "index": 84,
        "start_time": 277990,
        "end_time": 282396,
        "text": "think of the massive quantity captured\nin just these few symbols,"
    },
    {
        "index": 85,
        "start_time": 282396,
        "end_time": 285779,
        "text": "and see if you can come up \nwith a different way to represent it."
    }
]